# Permissions & Routing

RBAC is client-side: permissions arrive with the user's role (`getMyRole`) and are cached in `authStore`. The backend enforces authorization on every API call — frontend gating is UX only.

## Permission registry (`src/lib/rbac/constants/`)

- One file per domain: `product.ts`, `cart.ts`, `role.ts`, `shop.ts`, …
- Each exports an `as const` map (e.g. `PRODUCT_PERMISSIONS`) with string values matching backend permission names
- `index.ts` merges all maps into `RBAC_PERMISSIONS` via `mergePermissionMaps()` and exports `PermissionName` type
- Never use raw permission strings in feature code — import from `#/lib/rbac/constants`

```ts
export const PRODUCT_PERMISSIONS = {
  product_create: 'product:create',
  product_read: 'product:read',
  // …
} as const
```

When adding a new backend permission, add it to the matching constants file and ensure it flows through `RBAC_PERMISSIONS`.

## Reading permissions

| API | Location | Use for |
|---|---|---|
| `usePermissions()` | `src/lib/rbac/hooks.ts` | Full permission list |
| `useHasAllPermissions(all)` | `src/lib/rbac/hooks.ts` | AND check in components |
| `hasPermission(state, p)` | `src/stores/auth.store.ts` | Imperative check outside React |
| `hasAllPermissions` / `hasAnyPermission` | `src/stores/auth.store.ts` | Guard functions |

Permissions hydrate via `AuthBootstrap` → `getMyRole()` → `setMyRole()`. Don't read permissions from `localStorage` directly in feature code.

## Route-level guards

### Authentication

```ts
import { ensureAuthenticated } from '#/lib/auth-guards'

export const Route = createFileRoute('/me')({
  beforeLoad: ensureAuthenticated,
  // …
})
```

`ensureAnonymous()` redirects authenticated users away (sign-in/sign-up flows).

### Permission-gated routes

```ts
import { ensurePermission } from '#/lib/rbac/guards'
import { ROLE_PERMISSIONS } from '#/lib/rbac/constants'

export const Route = createFileRoute('/admin/roles')({
  beforeLoad: ensurePermission({
    all: [ROLE_PERMISSIONS.role_read],
    redirectTo: '/forbidden',
  }),
  // …
})
```

`ensurePermission` checks auth first (→ `/sign-in`), then `all` (AND) and/or `any` (OR) permission lists (→ `/forbidden` by default).

## Component-level gating

Use `<RequirePermission>` for conditional UI — routes stay reachable; the page decides what to show.

```tsx
import { RequirePermission } from '#/components/rbac/require-permission'
import { PRODUCT_PERMISSIONS } from '#/lib/rbac/constants'

<RequirePermission all={[PRODUCT_PERMISSIONS.product_create]}>
  <Button>Add product</Button>
</RequirePermission>
```

- `all` — every listed permission required (AND)
- `fallback` — rendered when check fails (default `null`)
- Combine route `beforeLoad` guards for whole-page access with `<RequirePermission>` for action buttons

## Auth store selectors

Read auth state through store selectors — never duplicate token/role logic:

```ts
import { useStore } from '@tanstack/react-store'
import { authStore, selectAccessToken, selectIsAuthenticated } from '#/stores/auth.store'

const accessToken = useStore(authStore, selectAccessToken)
```

For SSR-safe subscription in client components, prefer `useClientStore` from `#/hooks/use-client-store`.

## Anti-patterns

- Hardcoded permission strings (`'product:read'`) — use `PRODUCT_PERMISSIONS.product_read`
- Reading `localStorage` for role/permissions in feature code
- Assuming frontend gating is security — always handle 403 from API gracefully
- Permission-gating entire routes for individual button actions — use `<RequirePermission>` instead
- Skipping `beforeLoad: ensureAuthenticated` on private pages and relying only on loader redirects
